<TITLE> Tigers 321-5 at close, Tamim 128 </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, July 12 (bdnews24.com)  Bangladesh pushed their lead past 200 by stumps on the fourth day of the first Test against West Indies at Kingstown, St Vincent on Sunday. The Tigers had reached 321-5 which gave them a lead of 253 after a maiden Test hundred by opener Tamim Iqbal who made a superb 128 off 243 balls which was studded with 17 fours. The left-hander, with a maiden Test century after lunch, put on 146 runs with Junaed Siddique, before falling in the final session of the day with the score on 228. Junaed made a career-best 78 before departing on 258-3. Bangladesh then lost two quick wickets in the space of six runs. First Mohammad Ashraful went for 3 with the score reading 261-4 and then Raqibul Hasan (18). Mushfiqur Rahim and Shakib Al Hasan were batting on 28 and 26 respectively. The pair had added 54 runs for the unbroken sixth wicket. Bangladesh scored 238 all out in their first innings and then dismissed the hosts for
